  "prompt": "Does the US Federal government ever conduct pilot studies before launching big programs?",
  "response": "Yes, the U.S. federal government often conducts pilot studies or pilot programs before fully launching large-scale initiatives. These pilot studies help evaluate the feasibility, effectiveness, and potential impacts of the proposed programs or policies. By conducting these smaller-scale tests, the government can gather valuable data, identify any potential issues, and make necessary adjustments before implementing the program nationwide.\n\nExamples of pilot programs include initiatives in healthcare, education, technology, and social services. For instance, the Medicare program frequently tests new healthcare models in pilot studies before broader adoption. Similarly, education programs may be tested in select schools or districts before wider rollout. These pilot studies are a critical component of evidence-based policymaking and help ensure that large-scale programs are more likely to succeed and meet their intended objectives.",
